1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:30,021
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble

2
00:00:30,288 --> 00:00:31,789
and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:33,753 --> 00:00:54,860
So I'm mindful of the fact that one or two people here know very little about Buddhism, and some who know quite a lot, so I'll try and sort of weave a story that sort of encompasses both, and also talk about the Mahasi and the technique that we're using for Vipassana.

4
00:00:56,679 --> 00:01:01,786
When we practice meditation, I think we have to be clear about three things.

5
00:01:02,828 --> 00:01:07,213
First of all, what does the Buddha mean by right awareness?

6
00:01:09,356 --> 00:01:18,069
And then, how do we maintain that sort of awareness against all the hindrances, how the mind wanders off all the time?

7
00:01:19,792 --> 00:01:23,716
And what is it we're investigating?

8
00:01:24,811 --> 00:01:26,914
What is the process of liberation?

9
00:01:27,275 --> 00:01:28,275
What do we mean by that?

10
00:01:29,518 --> 00:01:31,521
What does the Buddha mean by delusion?

11
00:01:34,685 --> 00:01:38,370
So it's always good to start the story with the Buddha himself.

12
00:01:40,052 --> 00:01:44,900
He lived in what you might call an upper middle class.

13
00:01:48,304 --> 00:01:50,126
Well, I suppose almost nobility.

14
00:01:50,662 --> 00:01:59,179
His father was a head man of a group of people, a tribe called the Sakyas, and they were under the local king of Kosala.

15
00:01:59,859 --> 00:02:04,668
So all the stories about him being a very rich prince and all that is all later stuff.

16
00:02:05,209 --> 00:02:11,540
But he was brought up as a Kshatriya, which is the warrior caste, so he would have spent a lot of time

17
00:02:11,790 --> 00:02:14,813
learning how to use swords and spears and stuff like that.

18
00:02:15,395 --> 00:02:16,336
And also governance.

19
00:02:17,796 --> 00:02:21,121
But it's interesting to remember that he would have been illiterate.

20
00:02:24,525 --> 00:02:31,372
Writing as such was coming in, but it was coming in, much like it happened in Europe, I believe, in accounts.

21
00:02:32,592 --> 00:02:35,956
Businessmen keeping, business people keeping their accounts.

22
00:02:37,258 --> 00:02:40,801
But that didn't mean, of course, that the language wasn't highly developed.

23
00:02:41,609 --> 00:02:43,531
It was passed on through memory.

24
00:02:43,811 --> 00:02:49,977
So even today in Hinduism, the Rig Veda would be learnt off by heart by the Brahmins.

25
00:02:50,897 --> 00:02:52,118
And it's interesting how they do it.

26
00:02:52,180 --> 00:02:56,043
They first of all teach the child how to pronounce the syllables.

27
00:02:57,405 --> 00:03:00,106
Even before they know what it means, they pronounce the syllables.

28
00:03:00,707 --> 00:03:03,290
And then when they've got it off pat, then they tell them what it means.

29
00:03:04,131 --> 00:03:06,933
And only after they know what it means can they begin to philosophise.

30
00:03:07,955 --> 00:03:09,776
It's completely the opposite to what we do.

31
00:03:11,241 --> 00:03:15,385
We expect people to be philosophers and creative before they've got the basics.

32
00:03:16,967 --> 00:03:19,409
So that's the sort of society he lived in.

33
00:03:19,870 --> 00:03:21,050
And of course there were pleasures.

34
00:03:21,271 --> 00:03:22,473
There were lots of pleasures.

35
00:03:23,293 --> 00:03:29,800
And he would have had lots of free time as opposed to, say, the labourers and the lower caste.

36
00:03:29,819 --> 00:03:32,141
The caste system wasn't so rigid in his day.

37
00:03:32,382 --> 00:03:34,443
It was becoming so, but not so rigid.

38
00:03:35,784 --> 00:03:40,810
And it was to the east of him, out in present-day Calcutta, that sort of area,

39
00:03:41,481 --> 00:04:09,008
present day Bihar that the Brahmins were getting ascendancy before that the ruling caste, the warrior caste would have been considered higher than the Brahmins and there would seem to be some sort of disaffection with society going on, much like the hippies of the 70s and there were lots of men mainly men but often their wives and occasional women

40
00:04:09,376 --> 00:04:20,668
who would leave the homely life, who would leave household life, and live very basic lives out in the forests, and come in for alms round.

41
00:04:20,887 --> 00:04:25,192
So all that was established before the Buddha himself set out.

42
00:04:25,213 --> 00:04:31,860
There was an established custom of how to live the ascetic life.

43
00:04:32,600 --> 00:04:38,067
And it's thought to go back, right back to the Mahinda, was it Mahinda Dharo,

44
00:04:38,317 --> 00:05:06,822
civilization in the Indus Valley which somehow disappeared and we can't read any of their stuff but when the Aryans came down from the north and conquered all that area it seems as though some of their yogic practices and what not passed into their culture so it has a very long history this idea of ascetic practice and building up the powers that the mind has as opposed to the body

45
00:05:08,860 --> 00:05:12,766
Now at some point he gets fed up with the pleasures and joys of life.

46
00:05:13,848 --> 00:05:16,692
They become insipid, vapid, you might say.

47
00:05:17,814 --> 00:05:28,432
And because of that emptiness, that's one of the underlying reasons for him leaving his household life.

48
00:05:28,891 --> 00:05:33,079
But at a deeper level, it was what we would call an existential crisis.

49
00:05:33,886 --> 00:05:39,954
He came to realise that there was in fact sickness, ageing and death and that's where he was moving towards.

50
00:05:39,973 --> 00:05:43,718
And it's something I think that comes to all of us at the end of youth at some point.

51
00:05:44,399 --> 00:05:45,680
That's part of growing up.

52
00:05:46,901 --> 00:05:52,129
And normally speaking people start taking life a bit more seriously in their mid-twenties.

53
00:05:53,850 --> 00:06:03,403
Career, marriage, partnership, all that sort of stuff takes on a more serious sort of quality as they move towards a real

54
00:06:03,973 --> 00:06:30,791
involvement in social life in the life of society so at that time these things are sort of on his mind and it comes to a crisis point so he gets permission from his family, his wife to shoot off and spend some time as an aesthetic and if

55
00:06:30,973 --> 00:06:38,504
I don't know, I can only presume, this is just a personal presumption, that it was a bit like myself when I left, when I joined the Order.

56
00:06:39,225 --> 00:06:45,435
I said to my mother, who wept bitterly, can't understand why, that I would just go for three years.

57
00:06:45,536 --> 00:06:46,937
It was just trying it out.

58
00:06:47,519 --> 00:06:51,764
I just needed a bit of space, a bit of time, and that sort of stuff.

59
00:06:51,785 --> 00:06:56,172
And then, of course, you get habituated, I suppose.

60
00:06:56,192 --> 00:07:00,237
So anyway, he left with this, shall we say, this...

61
00:07:00,995 --> 00:07:03,798
deep psychological questioning about life.

62
00:07:03,898 --> 00:07:05,660
And it was something that was in the air.

63
00:07:06,521 --> 00:07:11,865
In that time, one thing that they were trying to escape was rebirth.

64
00:07:11,886 --> 00:07:13,228
So it was taken for granted.

65
00:07:13,307 --> 00:07:18,692
And not everybody, there were materialists, but it was taken for granted that you basically got reborn.

66
00:07:19,274 --> 00:07:20,815
And you could be reborn in any realm.

67
00:07:20,995 --> 00:07:22,216
You could be reborn as an animal.

68
00:07:23,017 --> 00:07:29,043
And the idea of being reborn wasn't all that happy an idea, especially back onto the earth.

69
00:07:29,665 --> 00:07:34,872
because it just meant going through the same old routine, work, sickness, aging and death.

70
00:07:36,314 --> 00:07:46,088
So there was a sort of existential fear that ran through the society at that time, which fueled this idea of trying to seek something which was beyond that.

71
00:07:47,149 --> 00:07:58,065
And so when the Buddha left, he left already into a set system, a set way of being an ascetic, set customs, can't call them rules, more like customs.

72
00:07:58,747 --> 00:07:59,588
There were...

73
00:07:59,803 --> 00:08:02,646
regular teachers, very well-known teachers of the time.

74
00:08:03,827 --> 00:08:15,800
It was one of the pastimes of the age to turn up at the park, these lovely parks that they had, bamboo park and so on, especially on a full moon.

75
00:08:16,901 --> 00:08:21,326
When in the east, for those of you who have been, as you know, you can actually see colour, it's that bright.

76
00:08:22,005 --> 00:08:28,612
And on the full moon they would all go to these parks and listen to the great debates and arguments of these ascetics that

77
00:08:29,149 --> 00:08:56,355
between each other and that was one of their entertainments that was before videos and stuff like that so he left the home life to join that sort of life and the first thing he tries is teachers who teach him how to attain blissful states all religions have these blissful states they're attained through prayer, through mantra and

78
00:08:57,482 --> 00:09:07,356
what we discover in that sort of technique, such as the metta we did, we can build up a very tremendous ecstasy within ourselves.

79
00:09:07,376 --> 00:09:13,206
The heart, although I was saying to you that when we practice metta, we don't worry about the emotions.

80
00:09:13,225 --> 00:09:15,788
It may be not feeling so good.

81
00:09:16,571 --> 00:09:17,993
It may be a bit depressed and whatnot.

82
00:09:18,373 --> 00:09:21,817
But eventually, the heart does begin to resonate with the will.

83
00:09:22,940 --> 00:09:26,544
And as you keep making these very gentle...

84
00:09:26,827 --> 00:09:34,678
the heart resonates more and more and they become quite internal ecstasies.

85
00:09:36,221 --> 00:09:41,048
Now, one of the benefits of being able to develop that sort of thing is that you're happy.

86
00:09:41,809 --> 00:09:46,135
You're happy while you're in the absorption and when you come out of it, it stays with you.

87
00:09:46,876 --> 00:09:49,782
It's not as though that mood suddenly disappears.

88
00:09:50,763 --> 00:09:55,570
And when you become an adept at such a thing, you can move in and out of that at will.

89
00:09:56,578 --> 00:10:06,629
And so you can understand how if you're going to find a way of being blissed out all the time, what do you worry about sex, drugs and rock and roll for?

90
00:10:07,068 --> 00:10:09,051
Or food or anything like that?

91
00:10:09,471 --> 00:10:16,758
You're quite happy under a tree with your loin cloth and you nip around for a bit of food every day and you don't mind what you eat.

92
00:10:17,479 --> 00:10:22,082
It's immaterial because all you want to do is just sustain the body so you can get back under your tree.

93
00:10:23,245 --> 00:10:23,784
So...

94
00:10:23,984 --> 00:10:34,472
That sort of blissful practice was already well developed, and he brought it into his teaching, and we call them the Jhanic states, the absorptions.

95
00:10:35,234 --> 00:10:40,278
And one of those practices is the metta we were doing this morning.

96
00:10:40,298 --> 00:10:53,028
But the problem is that these things do die out, and that underlying them, because they don't deal with problems, they don't deal with psychological problems, they definitely don't deal with the fear's

97
00:10:53,296 --> 00:10:55,438
and the aversion of sickness, aging, and death.

98
00:10:56,461 --> 00:11:06,774
And so whenever these things passed away, whenever the old thoughts returned, he realized that actually that wasn't an escape from suffering.

99
00:11:06,794 --> 00:11:13,164
It was like icing over dung, you might say, if I'll excuse the expression.

100
00:11:13,745 --> 00:11:18,392
So with that, he left his teachers, who taught him these absorptions.

101
00:11:19,856 --> 00:11:28,328
And then he tried, this is the normal chronology that you get taught, you see, but it's not absolutely clear which came first.

102
00:11:28,389 --> 00:11:32,293
But anyway, he then tried what's known as the ascetic practices.

103
00:11:33,095 --> 00:11:41,385
The main one was starvation, was really drawing the body down to its limit, you might say.

104
00:11:42,727 --> 00:11:45,611
So there were two major philosophies which...

105
00:11:46,063 --> 00:11:47,967
You can see even these days.

106
00:11:48,028 --> 00:11:52,798
The first was a materialist philosophy, which basically meant that you die and that's it.

107
00:11:52,817 --> 00:11:53,559
That's the end of it.

108
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:56,625
You may as well enjoy life as much as you can.

109
00:11:57,307 --> 00:12:03,600
And that was the idea of just enjoying the ordinary pleasures of life, but also these absorptions.

110
00:12:04,182 --> 00:12:05,845
At least you enjoyed life.

111
00:12:06,128 --> 00:12:19,243
Some thought that you had these absorptions, and then you went from rebirth to rebirth, right into higher and higher and more subtle levels of peacefulness and joy, and that was it.

112
00:12:19,504 --> 00:12:20,264
Then you disappeared.

113
00:12:20,644 --> 00:12:28,193
So there were all sorts of theories about how our life progressed.

114
00:12:28,214 --> 00:12:35,341
And on the other side, as opposed to that sort of nihilistic idea, annihilation,

115
00:12:35,659 --> 00:12:59,996
annihilationist idea excuse me so that everybody just annihilated at one point or another there were those of course who believed in an eternal soul and the soul was trapped in the body it was trapped by its karma karma had become physical it was your body and it was your attraction to the senses that kept you down at this level and therefore

116
00:13:00,178 --> 00:13:13,317
If one could let go of this through ascetic practices, then the soul would be released from the body, or the desire to be reborn in this realm, and it would rise into eternal bliss.

117
00:13:13,337 --> 00:13:16,582
So the Jains were very much into that sort of philosophy.

118
00:13:17,283 --> 00:13:21,971
And it's understood that the Buddha actually worked with them.

119
00:13:22,572 --> 00:13:26,878
He was his elder contemporary, the Jain leader, the Nigantha.

120
00:13:28,798 --> 00:13:37,893
And so the idea was, of course, the main thing was to not give any pleasure to the sense bases, you see.

121
00:13:40,277 --> 00:13:42,600
And he seems to have practiced this quite severely.

122
00:13:42,639 --> 00:13:45,043
He talks about holding his spine through his stomach.

123
00:13:45,644 --> 00:13:47,788
If you have a go at that, you'll see how thin he was.

124
00:13:49,630 --> 00:13:54,739
And at some point, he sort of wakes up and he realizes, actually, this is getting him nowhere either.

125
00:13:55,090 --> 00:13:57,394
And in fact, all it is, is more suffering.

126
00:13:57,413 --> 00:14:04,706
So he leaves his companions and they're quite disgusted with him because they think they've gone soft or he's lost his courage, you know.

127
00:14:05,687 --> 00:14:12,619
Remember that the James saints, the ones that they really praise, are the ones who finally stop eating.

128
00:14:12,639 --> 00:14:20,692
I mean, that's the way they would express their saintliness, just to finally stop eating and die, let go, you see.

129
00:14:23,221 --> 00:14:35,254
So we have this rather dejected young man by the roadside, and somebody comes along, we actually know her name, Sujata, means happy birth, with some offerings for the local god.

130
00:14:35,676 --> 00:14:41,402
Although it's sort of a sweet rice thing, but I much prefer rice pudding.

131
00:14:41,422 --> 00:14:50,493
And when she sees this poor wretch, in the scriptures, of course, they talk about her being bowled over by this god-like figure by the roadside.

132
00:14:50,552 --> 00:14:51,573
But I mean, if he's...

133
00:14:52,297 --> 00:14:55,159
If he's almost starving himself to death, it can hardly look like that.

134
00:14:56,020 --> 00:14:58,203
Anyway, he eats.

135
00:14:58,825 --> 00:15:04,230
He has this rice pudding, you see, which of course is a break away from all that ascetic practice.

136
00:15:04,731 --> 00:15:06,514
And it sort of revivifies him.

137
00:15:07,355 --> 00:15:12,561
And something happens at that point, which then brings about a turnaround in his practice.

138
00:15:12,620 --> 00:15:16,605
And it's because of this that we say he is self-enlightened.

139
00:15:16,625 --> 00:15:18,267
Up until now, there's no direction.

140
00:15:20,370 --> 00:15:21,291
He remembers...

141
00:15:21,692 --> 00:15:23,916
his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

142
00:15:23,936 --> 00:15:24,817
And he's a child.

143
00:15:25,418 --> 00:15:30,283
And he remembers the state that he was in when he's watching his father doing this ploughing ceremony.

144
00:15:31,504 --> 00:15:35,830
It's to open the sowing season.

145
00:15:35,850 --> 00:15:46,442
And he recognizes in that state the same attentiveness, the same concentration that he's been able to gain through his practice of the absorptions, the concentration practice.

146
00:15:46,943 --> 00:15:50,248
But there is within that also a question mark.

147
00:15:50,784 --> 00:16:00,234
So there's the child observing his father, completely absorbed in what's happening, and with the wonder, like, what is this all about?

148
00:16:00,335 --> 00:16:04,418
What's going to happen in his mind?

149
00:16:04,438 --> 00:16:10,264
And it's because of that little memory that he turns the whole process of meditation around upon itself.

150
00:16:10,865 --> 00:16:20,774
So instead of trying to find an escape from suffering, trying to find a place where there's no suffering, he turns around upon suffering to ask how suffering is caused in the first place.

151
00:16:21,548 --> 00:16:26,615
And it's with that inspiration that he sits under the Bodhi tree, which is the fig tree.

152
00:16:26,634 --> 00:16:27,537
It's a great big tree.

153
00:16:27,596 --> 00:16:29,278
It's lovely.

154
00:16:29,359 --> 00:16:31,121
On a hot day, you definitely want to sit under it.

155
00:16:32,102 --> 00:16:38,051
And it's there that he sits and makes this what we call the great determination.

156
00:16:39,133 --> 00:16:42,136
So there's the great renunciation when he leaves home.

157
00:16:42,557 --> 00:16:43,298
Everything's greater.

158
00:16:43,860 --> 00:16:46,663
And there's the great determination when he sits under the tree.

159
00:16:47,284 --> 00:16:51,149
And he determines because he sees no other...

160
00:16:51,534 --> 00:17:01,750
no other way of dealing with this existential crisis within himself, that he will sit and either he'll crack this problem or he'll die.

161
00:17:03,572 --> 00:17:10,402
Now, I always say, lucky for him and lucky for us, it only took six hours, according to the legends around him.

162
00:17:11,083 --> 00:17:18,453
And he makes this break, he makes this real breakthrough, and with it there comes this release from what he termed delusion, you see.

163
00:17:20,189 --> 00:17:25,214
So let's go back a bit and just talk about this right awareness.

164
00:17:25,476 --> 00:17:27,157
So it's the image of a child.

165
00:17:28,179 --> 00:17:31,542
I usually have a picture hanging up, but I've not had time yet to put it up.

166
00:17:33,085 --> 00:17:44,559
If you bring the image of a child, usually even up to the age of 10 sometimes, 10, 11, and they become absorbed in something, you notice what their face is like.

167
00:17:45,198 --> 00:17:46,740
Their eyes are fixated.

168
00:17:46,759 --> 00:17:51,787
If they see a bug or something they've never seen before, they just become completely absorbed.

169
00:17:51,807 --> 00:17:53,848
They lose a sense of all their surroundings.

170
00:17:54,049 --> 00:17:56,173
You can shout at them, but they're completely absorbed.

171
00:17:57,153 --> 00:17:58,234
And their mouth drops.

172
00:17:58,414 --> 00:17:59,237
They look gormless.

173
00:18:00,117 --> 00:18:05,664
So their parents usually tell them to close their mouths or a fly will go in or something.

174
00:18:05,684 --> 00:18:07,768
Give them a clip on the back of their head to tell them to wake up.

175
00:18:08,348 --> 00:18:13,955
And in so doing, of course, ruin that moment, its potential for full liberation, you see.

176
00:18:14,694 --> 00:18:17,877
So just think of that face, you see.

177
00:18:17,897 --> 00:18:25,645
So the fixation of the eyes, the complete absorption, the wonder, the wonder, and the jaw dropping.

178
00:18:26,506 --> 00:18:33,353
When the jaw drops, and this is why we say lips together, teeth apart, the jaw's relaxed, this is connected to your thinking.

179
00:18:34,114 --> 00:18:37,156
So the thinking stops, see.

180
00:18:37,176 --> 00:18:40,720
The thinking stops and there's just the watching, just the observing.

181
00:18:41,611 --> 00:18:48,880
And then when, of course, the child has absorbed what it is they're looking at, the question arises, what is it?

182
00:18:50,521 --> 00:18:53,746
And, of course, they're told that's a beetle or something.

183
00:18:54,847 --> 00:19:04,599
And as soon as the beetle is known, the word beetle, it attaches itself to an image in the mind that we call a perception.

184
00:19:05,560 --> 00:19:08,444
Every time that child from now on sees a beetle,

185
00:19:09,016 --> 00:19:10,317
It just says there's a beetle.

186
00:19:10,577 --> 00:19:12,119
It never really looks again.

187
00:19:13,142 --> 00:19:13,923
And that's where we are.

188
00:19:14,163 --> 00:19:25,318
We never get down to the direct experience of things because we presume the concept we have of it is a direct perception.

189
00:19:26,401 --> 00:19:33,651
So even when you look across at the meadows here and you see a tree, you'll know it's a tree.

190
00:19:33,991 --> 00:19:37,757
We see it's a tree, but we don't actually look at the tree

191
00:19:38,210 --> 00:19:43,435
in that same original way, the original mind, the beginner's mind of a child.

192
00:19:44,836 --> 00:20:01,634
The whole process of vipassana is to get back to that original mind, to get back to that non-conceptual way, non-thinking way, non-emergetic way of looking, feeling and experiencing things.

193
00:20:03,353 --> 00:20:08,161
And of course very difficult for us because ever since we were children we've been taught the opposite.

194
00:20:10,786 --> 00:20:26,593
The more literate, the more visual, the more we depend upon images, TV, all that sort of stuff, the less actually we're in contact with the sense bases as the sense base itself directly experiences something.

195
00:20:28,176 --> 00:20:36,849
So, for instance, if you go to a restaurant and you decide you can have a pizza or something, and you have a pizza, you already have an idea of a pizza.

196
00:20:37,711 --> 00:20:41,596
So the pizza turns up and it's not so good, it's a very good pizza.

197
00:20:42,258 --> 00:20:45,743
It's immediately compared with all the past pizzas.

198
00:20:46,545 --> 00:20:49,829
